<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> &quot;Last point to make tonight - you took my Clinton statement out of context. Go back and reread it. In context, you will see that when I state I would answer the questions if asked, I was referring to a congressional hearing. Not a public message board.&quot;<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Your point is well taken. Under oath you are saying that you would in fact answer the question. I believe we are talking past each other on this point after reviewing the previous posts. So let me clear up my end. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  I am saying that you found the questions I asked rude and insulting. I asked if you would really answer them before a congressional hearing, and doubted you would based upon your responses (I believe the distinction you make between answering such questions in a public forum or under oath really trivializes the nature of the point I was making: such questions are improper no matter where asked and do not deserve an answer). I also pointed out that such questions being asked of the President is equally as rude and should not have been asked to begin with. Dirty politics.<br>
<br>
I think we both agree that the questions should not be asked of the President (or similar questions), again &quot;dirty politics&quot;. We disagree over the end result if the questions are asked. You seem to be saying that the President was morally bound to answer such questions &quot;truthfully&quot;. No other answer would be &quot;right&quot; or &quot;good&quot;. In the case of Bill Clinton there was really only two options: answer the question &quot;truthfully&quot; or obfuscate the issue by telling a lie under oath. Silence is not an option in a congressional hearing. Especially if you are the President of the USA. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  We are going to disagree on the &quot;lie&quot; bit due, in part, because we are mutually confusing each other's view on ethics (very easy to do in a forum like this). Also, we percieve the &quot;moral world&quot; from two very different ethical systems. Neither the twain shall meet, I think. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  However, I believe that Clinton was right in trying to confuse the issue with his answer. I base my view over his lie in part on the point that the asking of the questions was not permissable and should never have been asked. I also believe that any red blooded married man who loves his family should lie to the grave about sexual impropriety to protect the reputation of his family, if he can get away with it. Why? Sex outside of marriage is a trivial thing and is not morally blameworthy. Hence should not be used as a test of morality. The only reason why there is a problem with sex outside of marriage is that the predominate moral view over sex in the USA is based upon an antiquated Puritan principle that sex is a necessary evil resulting from the fall of Adam and Eve. Recall that the view is Eve was cursed by God to bear children because of her sinful act at tempting Adam with the fruit of the Tree, hence the act of impregnation is &quot;evil&quot;, too.<br>
<br>
At any rate, the act of sex between consenting adults is not a moral act at all. It is simply a pleasurable biological function (again, some see &quot;pleasure&quot; as evil, too). I believe it is wrong to politicize sex, let alone force the issue of monogamy as some moral litmus test on our politicians. Knowing that many politicians like to appeal to Puritanical views over the &quot;morality&quot; of sex for political gain, I would have justified lying about the blow job from Monica, too, had I been Bill Clinton.<br>
<br>
